  <!-- Article Page for <article> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-article">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The &lt;article&gt; Tag: Your Content's Perfect Home</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-01">May 01, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>üåü Hey Frontend, Web Developers and Content Creators! Let's chat about something super cool‚Äîthe <article> tag in HTML5!</p>

        <p>This nifty little tag isn't just a container; it's designed to hold self-contained, independent pieces of content like your blog posts, news articles, or even product listings. Pretty neat, right?</p>
        
        <p>Imagine you're a newspaper editor. Each story needs its own container - complete with headline, byline, and content. That's exactly what <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> provides for the web.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <article style="border: 1px dashed var(--primary); padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h2>The Rise of Article Tag</h2>
            <p>Once upon a time, developers used endless divs. Then came the Article tag in HTML5 with semantic meaning...</p>
            <footer>By <span>zeroFiveJuly</span> | <time>May 01, 2025</time></footer>
          </article>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>So, why should you care about using &lt;article&gt; ?</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>‚úÖ Semantic Clarity:</strong> It helps make your content's structure and meaning clear to browsers and assistive technologies.</li>
            <li><strong>‚úÖ SEO Perks:</strong> It assists search engines in understanding the context and relevance of your key content‚Äîhello, better rankings!</li>
            <li><strong>‚úÖ Accessibility Boost:</strong> This is great news for users who rely on screen readers, making their experience smoother.</li>
            <li><strong>‚úÖ Content Reusability:</strong> It makes syndicating and repurposing your awesome content a breeze!</li>
            <li><strong>‚úÖ Clean Structure:</strong> Replaces generic <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> containers with meaning</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Real-World Uses</h2>
        <p>You should wrap these in <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>:</p>
        
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Blog Post --&gt;
&lt;article&gt;
  &lt;h2&gt;My Development Journey&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Content...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;

&lt;!-- Forum Post --&gt;
&lt;article&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;Help with CSS Grid&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;I'm having trouble with...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;

&lt;!-- Product Card --&gt;
&lt;article&gt;
  &lt;h2&gt;Premium HTML Course&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Learn semantic HTML...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;Enroll Now&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Microdata Integration</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;article itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/BlogPosting"&gt;
  &lt;h2 itemprop="headline"&gt;Advanced HTML Techniques&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"&gt;
    By &lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Jane Developer&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div itemprop="datePublished" content="2023-05-15"&gt;May 15, 2023&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div itemprop="articleBody"&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Content here...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>When NOT to use &lt;article&gt;:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>For UI components (use <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> instead)</li>
            <li>When content isn't independently distributable</li>
            <li>For comments within articles (use <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> unless they're substantive)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Let's keep creating amazing things together!</strong></p>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Article</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <aside> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-aside">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The &lt;aside&gt; Tag: Your Content's Sidekick</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-02">May 02, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Remember the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> tag! Image the main narrative of a webpage, the core story unfolding for the reader. Now, picture a gentle whisper, a related anecdote or a helpful piece of extra context sitting just beside it.</p> 
        <p>This is where the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> tag found its purpose. It was the container for content that was tangentially connected to the main flow, like a sidebar showcasing related articles about different cultures alongside a travel blog, or a brief author biography enriching a news report.</p>
       <p>Though separate, it added depth and flavour to the primary content. 
            Think of <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> as the whispered aside in a play - related to the main content but not central to the narrative.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <article style="border: 1px dashed var(--primary); padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h2>CSS Grid Layout</h2>
            <p>Grid has revolutionized how we create layouts...</p>
            
            <aside style="background: rgba(67, 97, 238, 0.1); padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 3px solid var(--primary);">
              <h3>Did You Know?</h3>
              <p>CSS Grid was first proposed in 2011 and became widely supported by 2017.</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why &lt;aside&gt; Matters:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Semantic Separation:</strong> Clearly marks supplementary content</li>
            <li><strong>Styling Hook:</strong> Often appears as a sidebar or pull-quote</li>
            <li><strong>Reader Options:</strong> Screen readers can skip or prioritize it</li>
            <li><strong>Content Hierarchy:</strong> Shows search engines what's primary vs secondary</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>When to Use It</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Pull Quote --&gt;
&lt;aside&gt;
  &lt;blockquote&gt;"Semantic HTML improves accessibility"&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;

&lt;!-- Glossary Term --&gt;
&lt;aside&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;What is ARIA?&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Accessible Rich Internet Applications...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;

&lt;!-- Advertisement --&gt;
&lt;aside&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;Sponsored&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;!-- Ad content --&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Dynamic Sidebar with CSS Grid</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: minmax(300px, 1fr) 250px;
  gap: 2rem;
}

main {
  grid-column: 1;
}

aside {
  grid-column: 2;
  position: sticky;
  top: 1rem;
  align-self: start;
}</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>Common Mistakes:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Using for completely unrelated content (breaks semantic meaning)</li>
            <li>Nesting multiple <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> without proper headings</li>
            <li>Overusing in mobile layouts where space is limited</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <nav> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-nav">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The &lt;nav&gt; Tag: Your Site's Roadmap</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-03">May 03, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Every great city thrives on clear street signs. Every great website relies on <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> ‚Äî the semantic cornerstone for its most essential links.</p> 
        <p>In the boundless expanse of the internet, intuitive pathways are vital. The <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> tag serves as a digital signpost, anchoring a website's navigation menus. Whether guiding shoppers through an e-commerce platform or providing a table of contents for a detailed article, <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> delivers structure and focus.</p>
        <p>More than a mere list of links, it boldly declares, ‚ÄúThis is how to explore this site,‚Äù empowering human visitors and search engine crawlers alike with seamless navigation.</P>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <nav style="background: var(--light); padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; border: 1px dashed var(--primary);">
            <ul style="display: flex; gap: 1rem; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li><a href="#" style="text-decoration: none; color: var(--primary);">Home</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="text-decoration: none; color: var(--primary);">Articles</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="text-decoration: none; color: var(--primary);">About</a></li>
            </ul>
          </nav>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why &lt;nav&gt; Matters:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Keyboard Navigation:</strong> Users can jump to it with shortcuts</li>
            <li><strong>SEO Significance:</strong> Search engines identify primary navigation</li>
            <li><strong>Screen Reader Friendly:</strong> Announced as a navigation landmark</li>
            <li><strong>Future-Proof:</strong> Prepares for emerging navigation patterns</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Best Practices</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Main Navigation --&gt;
&lt;nav aria-label="Primary"&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="/"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="/articles"&gt;Articles&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;

&lt;!-- Table of Contents --&gt;
&lt;nav aria-label="Table of Contents"&gt;
  &lt;ol&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#intro"&gt;Introduction&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#chapter1"&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Mega Menu Pattern</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;nav aria-label="Main"&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
      &lt;a href="/products" aria-haspopup="true"&gt;Products&lt;/a&gt;
      &lt;div class="mega-menu"&gt;
        &lt;div class="mega-menu-column"&gt;
          &lt;h3&gt;Category 1&lt;/h3&gt;
          &lt;ul&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="/products/1"&gt;Product 1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;/ul&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;

&lt;style&gt;
  .mega-menu {
    display: none;
    position: absolute;
    /* Positioning styles */
  }
  
  li:hover .mega-menu {
    display: grid;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>Accessibility Considerations:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Always provide keyboard navigation support</li>
            <li>Use <code>aria-current="page"</code> for current page indicators</li>
            <li>Mobile menus should be fully operable via screen readers</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert">
          <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Don't wrap every link group in <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>. Reserve it for <em>major</em> navigation blocks.</p>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <figure> and <figcaption> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-figure">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The Dynamic Duo: &lt;figure&gt; & &lt;figcaption&gt;</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-04">May 04, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Imagine wandering through a museum where paintings hang without labels‚Äîbeautiful but bewildering. That's what images on the web are like without <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code>: a semantic duo that anchors visuals to their meaning. 
        <p>Every image, illustration, or media element carries a story. The <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> tag serves as the frame, elegantly containing these visual treasures. Yet, it's the <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code>, nestled within, that breathes life into them with a descriptive caption. Picture a photo of The Grail Center in Akwa-Ibom, its caption unveiling its cultural significance or a code snippet paired with text clarifying its purpose.</p>
        <p>Together, <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code> weave context and clarity, making media richer, more accessible, and universally understood.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <figure style="border: 1px dashed var(--primary); padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/1108099/pexels-photo-1108099.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=600" alt="Cute Dogs" style="width: 100%; height: auto;">
            <figcaption style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.5rem;">
              Figure 1: Two Yellow Labrador Retriever Puppies
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why This Pair Matters:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Screen readers announce the caption with the image</li>
            <li><strong>SEO Value:</strong> Search engines understand the image-content relationship</li>
            <li><strong>Responsive Ready:</strong> Maintains connection even when layout changes</li>
            <li><strong>Styling Control:</strong> Perfect for creating consistent media blocks</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Beyond Just Images</h2>
        <p>These tags work with various content types:</p>
        
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Code Snippet Example --&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;
  &lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;function greet() { 
  console.log("Hello World!"); 
}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
  &lt;figcaption&gt;Listing 1: Basic JavaScript function&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;!-- Video Example --&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;
  &lt;video controls src="tutorial.mp4"&gt;&lt;/video&gt;
  &lt;figcaption&gt;Video 1: Semantic HTML tutorial&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;!-- Data Visualization --&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;
  &lt;svg&gt;&lt;!-- Chart markup --&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;figcaption&gt;Chart 1: Monthly traffic growth&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Responsive Art Direction</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;figure&gt;
  &lt;picture&gt;
    &lt;source media="(min-width: 1200px)" srcset="large.jpg"&gt;
    &lt;source media="(min-width: 800px)" srcset="medium.jpg"&gt;
    &lt;img src="small.jpg" alt="Responsive image example"&gt;
  &lt;/picture&gt;
  &lt;figcaption&gt;Example of responsive art direction&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>When to Avoid:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>For decorative images that don't need captions</li>
            <li>When the image is purely for layout purposes</li>
            <li>If the caption doesn't add meaningful context</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert">
          <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Always include <code>alt</code> text for images <em>and</em> meaningful captions - they serve different purposes!</p>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <details> and <summary> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-details">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>&lt;details&gt; & &lt;summary&gt;: Your Built - In Accordion</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-05">May 05, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Picture a treasure chest with a labeled latch, tempting you to lift it. The <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;summary&gt;</code> tags bring that sense of discovery to the web - no JavaScript required!</p> 
        <p>Webpages often conceal extra layers of knowledge, ready to be uncovered. The <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> tag serves as the chest, safeguarding these hidden insights. Its companion, <code>&lt;summary&gt;</code>, acts as the inviting latch, displaying a clickable heading that sparks curiosity.</p> 
        <p>Imagine an FAQ where questions in <code>&lt;summary&gt;</code> unlock answers within <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> or technical specs revealed with a single click. Together, they create interactive, user-driven experiences with pure HTML finesse.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <details style="border: 1px solid var(--primary); border-radius: 0.3rem; padding: 0.5rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
  <summary style="font-weight: bold; cursor: pointer;">What is semantic HTML?</summary>
  <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Semantic HTML uses tags like <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> to describe the meaning of content, improving accessibility and SEO.</p>
</details>
          
          <details style="border: 1px solid var(--primary); border-radius: 0.3rem; padding: 0.5rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <summary style="font-weight: bold; cursor: pointer;">Click to reveal secret HTML tip</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">You can style the marker with <code>::marker</code> pseudo-element!</p>
          </details>

          <details style="border: 1px solid var(--primary); border-radius: 0.3rem; padding: 0.5rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
  <summary style="font-weight: bold; cursor: pointer;">Why use &lt;details&gt; instead of JavaScript?</summary>
  <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">The <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> tag provides native interactivity, reducing code complexity and ensuring compatibility with screen readers and low-bandwidth devices.</p>
</details>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why This Combo Rocks:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Zero JavaScript:</strong> Works even with JS disabled</li>
            <li><strong>Progressive Disclosure:</strong> Perfect for FAQs and technical docs</li>
            <li><strong>Built-In Accessibility:</strong> Keyboard operable by default</li>
            <li><strong>Performance Friendly:</strong> No library overhead</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Creative Implementations</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- FAQ Section --&gt;
&lt;details&gt;
  &lt;summary&gt;What is semantic HTML?&lt;/summary&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Semantic HTML means using elements that convey meaning...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;

&lt;!-- Spoiler Protection --&gt;
&lt;details&gt;
  &lt;summary&gt;Spoiler: Who wins in Avengers?&lt;/summary&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Iron Man sacrifices himself...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;

&lt;!-- Mobile-Friendly Menu --&gt;
&lt;details&gt;
  &lt;summary&gt;Menu&lt;/summary&gt;
  &lt;nav&gt;
    &lt;ul&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;About&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Nested Accordion Pattern</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;details&gt;
  &lt;summary&gt;Main Category&lt;/summary&gt;
  &lt;details&gt;
    &lt;summary&gt;Subcategory 1&lt;/summary&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Content...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/details&gt;
  &lt;details&gt;
    &lt;summary&gt;Subcategory 2&lt;/summary&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Content...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/details&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>Browser Quirks:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Firefox shows animation by default (can be disabled with <code>transition: height 0s</code>)</li>
            <li>IE11 requires polyfill for proper functionality</li>
            <li>Some screen readers may announce state changes differently</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert">
          <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Use <code>details[open]</code> in CSS to style the open state differently!</p>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <mark> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-mark">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The &lt;mark&gt; Tag: Your Digital Highlighter</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-06">May 06, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Picture studying a dense document, highlighter in hand, marking words that leap off the page. The <code>&lt;mark&gt;</code> tag brings that focus to the web, acting as a digital highlighter with semantic strength.</p>
        <p>Applied to text, it visually emphasizes key phrases, but its true power lies in meaning: it signals relevance. Use it to spotlight search terms in results or critical points in a quote, anchoring their importance within context.</p>
        <p>Like neon streaks in a textbook, <code>&lt;mark&gt;</code> makes the web's key moments unmissable, for both readers and search engines.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <p style="margin: 1rem 0;">
            When searching for "semantic HTML", results should <mark style="background: var(--accent); color: white; padding: 0.1em 0.3em;">highlight</mark> relevant terms to show why they matched your query.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why &lt;mark&gt; Beats Generic Spans:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Semantic Meaning:</strong> Indicates <em>relevance</em> in context</li>
            <li><strong>Search-Friendly:</strong> Google may prioritize marked content</li>
            <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Screen readers can announce highlights</li>
            <li><strong>Styling Control:</strong> Easy to customize appearance</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Practical Applications</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Search Results --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Your search for "HTML" found:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn &lt;mark&gt;HTML&lt;/mark&gt; semantics in 30 days...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;!-- Tutorial Emphasis --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Remember: Always include &lt;mark&gt;alt text&lt;/mark&gt; for images.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;!-- User-Generated Highlights --&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;The &lt;mark&gt;article&lt;/mark&gt; element changed how we structure content.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;footer&gt;- Student highlight&lt;/footer&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Search Highlight Animation</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>mark {
  background: linear-gradient(yellow, yellow);
  background-size: 0 100%;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  transition: background-size 0.5s ease;
}

mark.animate {
  background-size: 100% 100%;
}</code></pre>
        </div> -->
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>Semantic Misuse:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Don't use for styling only (use <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> with class)</li>
            <li>Avoid marking large text blocks (breaks semantic meaning)</li>
            <li>Not suitable for permanent highlights (use <code>&lt;strong&gt;</code> instead)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert">
          <p><strong>Design Tip:</strong> Customize the highlight color with CSS while preserving semantics:</p>
          <pre><code>mark {
  background: linear-gradient(yellow, yellow);
  padding: 0.1em;
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Page for <cite> -->
  <section class="article-page" id="article-cite">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="article-body">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>The &lt;cite&gt; Tag: Giving Credit Where It's Due</h1>
          <div class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-05-07">May 07, 2025</time></div>
        </header>

        <p>Imagine submitting a research paper without citations (that's academic disaster!).</p> 
        <p>The web's equivalent is the <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> tag, a semantic nod to crediting creative works. Every story or insight builds on others' contributions, and <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> ensures they're acknowledged. It wraps the title of a work‚Äîbe it a book, article, song, or film‚Äîgiving context and attribution.</p>
        <p>Often styled in italics by browsers, it signals provenance, like citing <cite>Things Fall Apart by Chinua Achebe</cite> in a literary essay or referencing a groundbreaking study. <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> weaves a web of trust, grounding knowledge in its sources.</p>

        <div class="live-example">
          <div class="example-title">Live Example:</div>
          <blockquote style="border-left: 3px solid var(--primary); padding-left: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <p>"Semantic HTML is the foundation of accessible web development."</p>
            <footer>‚Äî <cite style="font-style: italic;">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)</cite></footer>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="benefits">
          <h3>Why &lt;cite&gt; Matters:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Machine-Readable:</strong> Helps search engines understand references</li>
            <li><strong>Academic Integrity:</strong> Proper source attribution</li>
            <li><strong>Styling Hook:</strong> Italic by default but customizable</li>
            <li><strong>Semantic Clarity:</strong> Distinguishes citations from regular text</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Correct Usage</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;!-- Creative Work Title --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My favorite book is &lt;cite&gt;Eloquent JavaScript&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;!-- Quote Attribution --&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;"The web should be accessible to everyone."&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;footer&gt;‚Äî &lt;cite&gt;Tim Berners-Lee&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/footer&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;!-- Reference in Text --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As explained in &lt;cite&gt;HTML: The Living Standard&lt;/cite&gt;...&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h2>Advanced Implementations</h2>
        
        <h3>Biblographic References with Microdata</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <pre><code>&lt;p&gt;
  From the book &lt;cite itemprop="citation" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Book"&gt;
    &lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;HTML5: The Missing Manual&lt;/span&gt;
    by &lt;span itemprop="author"&gt;Matthew MacDonald&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/cite&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
        </div>
        
        <h3>Edge Cases</h3>
        <div class="alert warning">
          <p><strong>Common Confusions:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Not for personal names (use <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;address&gt;</code>)</li>
            <li>Avoid using for publication dates (use <code>&lt;time&gt;</code>)</li>
            <li>Don't nest other semantic elements inside <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert">
          <p><strong>Important:</strong> Use <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> for the <em>title of the work</em>, not the author's name. For people, use <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> or semantic classes.</p>
        </div>

        <a href="#articles" class="cta-button">Back to Articles</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

